GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 2
HOUSE BILL 908
Committee Substitute Favorable 4/29/25
Short Title: Modify Civil Commitment Hearing Procedures. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
April 14, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MODIFY THE PROCEDURES RELATED TO NOTICE AND VENUE FOR
3 CIVIL COMMITMENT HEARINGS.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 122C-268(c) reads as rewritten:
6 "(c) If the respondent's custody order indicates that he the respondent was charged with a
7 violent crime, including a crime involving an assault with a deadly weapon, and that he the
8 respondent was found incapable of proceeding, the clerk shall give notice of the time and place
9 of the hearing to the chief district judge and the district attorney in the county in which the
10 defendant was found incapable of proceeding as provided in G.S. 122C-264(d). The district
11 attorney in the county in which the respondent was found incapable of proceeding may represent
12 the State's interest at the hearing. If the district attorney elects to represent the State's interest,
13 upon motion of the district attorney, the venue for the hearing, rehearings, and supplemental
14 rehearings shall be the county in which the respondent was found incapable of proceeding."
15 SECTION 2. G.S. 122C-277(b) reads as rewritten:
16 "(b) If the respondent was initially committed as the result of conduct resulting in his the
17 respondent being charged with a violent crime, including a crime involving an assault with a
18 deadly weapon, and respondent was found incapable of proceeding, 15 days before the
19 respondent's discharge or conditional release the attending physician shall notify facility shall
20 notify the district attorney of the district where the respondent was found incapable of proceeding
21 and the clerk of superior court of the county in which the facility is located of his or her
22 determination regarding the proposed discharge or conditional release. The clerk shall then
23 schedule a rehearing to determine the appropriateness of respondent's release under the standards
24 of commitment set forth in G.S. 122C-271(b). The clerk shall give notice as provided in
25 G.S. 122C-264(d). The district attorney of the district where respondent was found incapable of
26 proceeding may represent the State's interest at the hearing. If the district attorney elects to
27 represent the State's interest, upon motion of the district attorney, the venue for the hearing,
28 rehearings, and supplemental rehearings shall be the county in which the respondent was found
29 incapable of proceeding."
30 SECTION 3. This act is effective when it becomes law and applies to commitment
31 hearings initiated on or after that date.
